RECON
  Fly a reconnaissance mission along a path, reporting on every sector
  overflown, then land at the destination.

SYNTAX
  recon <spy-plane-spec> <escort-plane-spec> <ap-sect> <path|dest>
  sweep <spy-plane-spec> <escort-plane-spec> <ap-sect> <path|dest>

DESCRIPTION
  Unlike bomb/fly, which only care about the final target, recon's
  entire value is reporting on every sector along the way. This is how
  spy-capable planes (like the E2-C Hawkeye) actually get used — they
  can't bomb or launch, they fly recon instead.

  <spy-plane-spec>    - planes intended to do the reporting. "none" or
                         "~" for no planes of this role, or anything
                         'plane' accepts: a uid, a uid range, a comma
                         list, "*", or a wing letter (see 'info wingadd').
  <escort-plane-spec>  - fighter/escort planes flying along for defense.
                         Same spec forms, or "none"/"~" for no escorts.
  <ap-sect>            - assembly point, player-relative "X,Y". Both
                         plane lists must currently be sitting exactly
                         at this sector (see KNOWN GAPS).
  <path|dest>          - a direction-string route (u/j/n/b/g/y, 'h' to
                         stop early) or a destination "X,Y" to auto-path
                         toward, same as 'navigate'/'march'.

  Report detail at each sector depends on which capable planes are
  still alive in the flight — this is recomputed at every step, so
  losing your spy plane partway through downgrades the rest of the
  report to the generic form:
    SPY-capable survivors present  - full intel report: sector econ/
                                     military stats (fuzzed the same
                                     way a satellite's spy report is —
                                     see 'info satellite'), plus ship
                                     and land unit rosters at that
                                     exact sector
    no SPY capability              - generic report: just the sector's
                                     type and a rounded efficiency
                                     estimate, plus a bare notice if a
                                     foreign nation has ships or land
                                     units there (no numbers, no roster)
    sea sectors                    - always just "flying over water",
                                     regardless of capability

  At the end of the path, surviving planes land — the destination must
  be a friendly airfield or harbor, same requirement as 'fly'.

KNOWN GAPS (v1)
  - No assembly-point range-gathering: 4.4.1 lets planes anywhere
    within range of the assembly point join the mission. Here, planes
    must already be sitting exactly at <ap-sect>.
  - No Anti-Sub Patrol report variant (a plane with ASW capability
    but no SPY capability gets the generic report, not a specialized
    submarine-patrol one).
  - A single combined interception check happens at the destination
    only, not per-hex flak/interception along the route (same
    simplification 'bomb' already makes).
  - No news event is filed for recon missions (matches 4.4.1 — it
    doesn't file one either).

  'sweep' is not just an alias: it additionally attempts to clear
  naval mines from sea sectors overflown. See 'info sweep' for that
  mechanic — it doesn't change anything described above.

EXAMPLE
  recon 5 none 0,0 jjn              plane 5 alone, no escort, from your
                                     capital, flies right-right-lower-right
  recon 5 6 0,0 4,2                 plane 5 with escort 6, auto-path to 4,2
  sweep c none 0,0 jj                every plane in wing c flies sweep

